The problem is `IFormFile` buffers the entire request body into memory. The fix has two parts: **raise the size limits** and **stream the multipart body directly to disk** using `MultipartReader`.

### 1. Configure Kestrel & form limits

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(o =>
{
    o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
});
```

### 2. Stream to disk — skip IFormFile entirely

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType ||
        !MediaTypeHeaderValue.TryParse(request.ContentType, out var mt) ||
        !HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary).Length.Equals(0))
    {
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");
    }

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(mt.Boundary).Value!;
    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) is not null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd) ||
            !cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            continue; // skip non-file fields
        }

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName();          // safe name
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var fs = new FileStream(
            savePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write,
            FileShare.None, bufferSize: 81920);

        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);               // streamed, never fully buffered
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

### 3. Disable request-body buffering (optional but recommended)

```csharp
// If you use any middleware that enables buffering:
app.Use(async (ctx, next) =>
{
    ctx.Request.EnableBuffering(bufferThreshold: 1024 * 64); // only 64 KB in memory
    await next();
});
```

### Why this works

| Approach | Memory use for 2 GB file |
|---|---|
| `IFormFile` | **~2 GB** (buffered) |
| `MultipartReader` | **~80 KB** (stream buffer) |

`MultipartReader` reads the raw request stream chunk-by-chunk and `CopyToAsync` writes each chunk straight to the `FileStream`—the full file is never in memory.

### Key gotchas

- **Reverse proxy limits** — if behind Nginx/IIS, raise `client_max_body_size` / `maxAllowedContentLength` there too.
- **Don't call `Request.Form`** anywhere before your endpoint—it triggers full buffering.
- **Validate early** — check `Content-Length` header before streaming to reject obviously oversized requests fast.
